Durban - A 7-day intelligence-driven operation by police to rid the province of illegal firearms has resulted in positive results. Forty-three suspects were arrested and a total of 42 illegal firearms and 624 rounds of ammunition were confiscated KZN police confirmed. "The recovered firearms include 38 handguns, two homemade firearms and one shotgun," said Lieutenant Colonel Thulani Zwane. Zwane said all the accused appeared in various courts around the province facing possession of illegal firearms and ammunition charges. "KwaZulu-Natal police officers are continuously targeting various places in the province in an attempt to get rid of illegal firearms and ammunition in the hands of criminals," said Zwane. The raids were conducted in various clusters which included EThekwini, Umgungundlovu, Umkhanyakude, Umzinyathi, King Cetshwayo, Uthukela and Zululand Cluster. Police said all the recovered firearms will be subject to ballistic tests to establish if they were used in any other crimes in the province. Daily News